Dear Mrs. Price:



Governor Beverly Eaves Perdue asked that I respond to your email regarding your mother’s Medicaid eligibility through the Special Assistance program.  The Division of Medical Assistance (DMA) administers the Medicaid program in North Carolina.  Please be assured of my interest and concern for your situation.



When an individual is living in an assisted living facility, they may be eligible for Medicaid if they meet the Special Assistance (SA) program requirements.  To be eligible for SA, an individual must be eligible for SSI, or ineligible for SSI solely due to income.  SA recipients are automatically eligible for Medicaid. 



Some assisted living facilities include a special care unit such as your mother’s Alzheimer’s unit.  To be eligible for SA in the special care unit and therefore receive automatic Medicaid, the individual’s income must be less than the SA rate set by the North Carolina General Assembly (currently $1,515 per month) plus the personal needs allowance (currently $46 per month).  The total monthly income limit for SA eligibility is $1,561.   Your mother’s income of $1,700 per month makes her ineligible for this program.



As you mention, your mother may be eligible for long term care Medicaid in a skilled nursing facility (nursing home).  The income eligibility requirements for this are different from the SA requirements.  Unfortunately, there are no exceptions that would allow your mother to qualify under the SA program.



