Thank you for your recent inquiry to the Governor’s Office.  They have asked that I respond.  I am glad to address the question of where the lottery funds have gone.



Through yesterday, sales to date have been over $ 3.5 billion.   We make transfers to the Office of State Budget and Management quarterly.  Our last transfer was made July 1 and was based on sales through the end of June.  We have transferred over $1.136 billion to North Carolina. Once we transfer funds, our responsibility for the funds is complete.



The Lottery Act specifies how the lottery proceeds will be spent.  The Act designates that 50% is to be split between at-risk four-year old pre-K and K-3 class size reduction; 40% to school construction; and 10% to college scholarships.  The class size dollars are the only lottery funds designated to cover teacher salaries. It takes an act of the Governor or the Legislature to alter this designation.  The following hot links list the lottery allocations by county for fiscal years 07 and 08:  <http://www.nc-educationlottery.org/uploads/docs/Beneficiary%20Brochure%20fy2008.pdf>FY '08 Beneficiary Brochure   <http://www.nc-educationlottery.org/uploads/docs/Beneficiary%20Brochure%20fy2007.pdf>FY '07 Beneficiary Brochure.  The FY09 brochure will be prepared after the fiscal year ends.  These brochures don’t show what the counties have received this year because we don’t have that information yet. You can find more information on the lottery webpage at <http://www.nc-educationlottery.org/about_where-the-money-goes.aspx>http://www.nc-educationlottery.org/about_where-the-money-goes.aspx.



The education lottery has accomplished what the Legislature envisioned when it was created.  The money is going where directed by law.  The lottery was never designed to meet all the budget needs of education.  We cover roughly 4% of the education budget.  The education budget is greater than 50% of the total state budget.  The K-12 annual budget is over $8 billion.  Education funding needs are significant.  At the lottery, we are extremely pleased that we have added over $1 billion that was not previously available.  The Governor is trying to fill a one-year $3 billion hole in the budget.  Without the lottery, that hole would be bigger.



Getting the word out about where the money has gone has proven difficult.  We appreciate the interest of citizens such as you and are glad to be able to provide this information





